<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhigila" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" genus="Thesium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thesium muasyae" order="Santalales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muasyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Thesium muasyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected on the limestone ridges, south east of Vanderstelskraal Farm, Overberg, Bredasdorp District, Western Cape Province, South Africa (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Map of A South Africa with the red outline indicating the Greater Cape Floristic Region (GCFR) B the GCFR showing the type locality (red solid circle) of Thesium muasyae and of the congener species, T. hispidulum (aqua solid stars), T. karooicum (blue solid triangles) and T. sonderianum (fuchsia solid squares)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.201.80774.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702533" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
, triangles) at elevations less than 80 m above sea level. This species occurs on limestone and shale-limestone ecotone scrubs. The limestone soil in the type locality is characterised mainly by calcium carbonate, tiny fossils and other fossilized debris from the coastal limestone of the Bokkerveld Group (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1533/9781782423928.1.37" author="Finch, HJS" journalOrPublisher="Phytochemical Bulletin of Botanical Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B6" refString="Finch, HJS, Samuel, AM, Lane, GPF, 2014. Soils and soil management. Woodhead Publishing Series in Food Science, Technology and Nutrition, Lockhart &amp; Wiseman's Crop Husbandry Including Grassland (9th edn.), Woodhead Publishing, 37-62. https://doi.org/10.1533/9781782423928.1.37" title="Soils and soil management. Woodhead Publishing Series in Food Science, Technology and Nutrition, Lockhart &amp; Wiseman's Crop Husbandry Including Grassland (9 th edn.), Woodhead Publishing, 37 - 62." url="https://doi.org/10.1533/9781782423928.1.37" year="2014">Finch et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jafrearsci.2017.10.011" author="Penn-Clarke, CR" journalOrPublisher="Journal of African Earth Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="157 - 178" refId="B22" refString="Penn-Clarke, CR, Rubidge, BS, Jinnah, ZA, 2018. Two hundred years of palaeontological discovery: Review of research on the Early to Middle Devonian Bokkeveld Group (Cape Supergroup) of South Africa. Journal of African Earth Sciences 137: 157 - 178, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jafrearsci.2017.10.011" title="Two hundred years of palaeontological discovery: Review of research on the Early to Middle Devonian Bokkeveld Group (Cape Supergroup) of South Africa." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jafrearsci.2017.10.011" volume="137" year="2018">Penn-Clarke et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Physically, the limestone soil is grey to whitish brown.
</paragraph>
